-- BHP, Capital Shopping, Uranium One: South African Stocks Preview
-- B y   C a r l i   L o u r e n s
-- 2010-12-17T06:09:17Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-17/bhp-capital-shopping-uranium-one-south-african-equity-market-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in South Africa.
Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names and prices
are from the last close.  South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index  advanced for
the third day, climbing 36.97, or 0.1 percent, to 31,703.61 at
the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg on Dec. 15. The exchange was
closed for trade yesterday, a public holiday in South Africa.  Adcock Ingram Holdings Ltd.  (AIP SJ): Africa’s largest
over-the-counter drugs company, said it will ask South Africa’s
National Treasury for an explanation of how an anti-AIDS drugs
tender was awarded after rivals won a bigger share of the order,
Business Day reported, citing Chief Executive Officer Jonathan
Louw. Adcock fell 3 cents, or 0.1 percent, to 58.96 rand.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BIL SJ): BHP said yesterday it reached a
three-year pay accord with the National Union of Metalworkers of
South Africa, ending a strike at its South African aluminum
smelters which began on Dec. 8. The stock fell 99 cents, or 0.4
percent, to 267.51 rand.  Capital Shopping Centres Group Plc  (CSO SJ): The U.K.
shopping mall-owner that rejected a bid from Simon Property
Group Inc. was raised to “Hold” from “Sell” at Oriel
Securities by equity analyst Charlie Foster. The stock rose 1.50
rand, or 3.6 percent, to 43.75 rand.  PBT Group Ltd.  (PBT SJ): The business intelligence gatherer
reported profit of 20 million rand for the 14 months ended Aug.
31. The stock rose 5 cents, or 4 rand, to 1.30 rand.  Uranium One Inc.  (UUU SJ):  ARMZ Uranium Holding Co. will
invest $300 million to $400 million in Mantra Resources Ltd.,
while unit Uranium One Inc. will fund Mantra’s capital spending.
ARMZ Chief Executive Officer Vadim Zhivov said yesterday. The
shares fell 1.51 rand, or 4.6 percent, to 31.49 rand.  Shares or American depositary receipts of the following
South African companies closed as follows:  Anglo American Plc (AAUKY US) added 1.2 percent to $24.34.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) lost 2.7 percent to $47.92. BHP
Billiton Ltd. (BBL US) rose 0.5 percent to $78.32. DRDGold Ltd.
(DROOY US) fell 0.8 percent to $4.76. Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI US)
declined 1.6 percent to $17.65. Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HMY US)
lost 1.4 percent to $12.34. Impala Platinum Holdings Co. (IMPUY
US) fell 0.3 percent to $32.56. Sappi Ltd. (SPP US) gained 0.6
percent to $5. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) added 0.9 percent to $48.47.
Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TLKGY US) fell 0.9 percent to $20.91.  To contact the reporter on this story:
